<TEXT>
the us armys school of the americas is 
teaching officers from latin america how to fight the narcotics 
trade 
the students are concerned about narcotics said col 
william a depalo jr commandant of the school at fort benning 
they recognize it as not only a threat to the united states but 
its now become apparent to them through an increased number of 
drug addicts in their own countries 
the school relocated from the panama canal zone in 1984 under 
the terms of the uspanama canal treaties trains military 
personnel from 18 latin american nations said depalo 
six new courses are aimed at violent drug traffickers depalo 
said subjects include use of ranger units strategic intelligence 
and disarming booby traps 
the classes range in length from a month to a year the school 
has no structured semestertype system and individual officers set 
up their own schedules 
depalo who is fluent in spanish visits a latin american 
country each month to meet with military leaders to promote the 
school and to make sure its courses are relevant 
as far as winning the battle against drug trafficking the key 
will be in getting the countries to limit and supress the supply 
he said 
they say we need to do more on our end in controlling 
consumption and theyre right depalo said this thing has to 
be attacked consistently and unrelentingly but at least the 
american public has awakened to the fact it appears that this is 
a serious national security threat more serious than the soviet 
union at this point 
the school of the americas founded in panama in 1947 has 
trained more than 50000 officers and enlisted military personnel 
from latin america it moved to the united states in 1984 after 
this country and panama were unable to reach an agreement that 
would have kept it operating in panama 
