<TEXT>
five soviet engineers came to study 
building design nine mexicans flew in to check disaster 
preparedness japan wanted precise detail on how much the earth 
moved new york city police looked at emergency response 
for all its havoc last weeks earthquake is now an 
international case study for experts focusing on how and why the 
earth convulses what structures survive its tremors and how to 
save shaken lives 
if theres any comfort for the people who lost loved ones it 
may be that all professionals learn from each one of these 
disasters it means we can do better the next time said ian 
buckle deputy director of the national center for earthquake 
engineering research in buffalo ny 
in a sense it is a laboratory teams from around the world 
will come to learn from this he said 
buckle was appointed by gov george deukmejian to investigate 
the collapse of the elevated twotiered section of interstate 880 
in oakland where people and vehicles were smashed between slabs of 
concrete and steel 
the freeway was built in 1957 before design load requirements 
were tightened because of lessons learned in the 1971 san fernando 
earthquake buckle said existing roads and bridges were supposed 
to be upgraded to conform to new codes 
new bridges were not just designed for strength but ductility 
the ability to be pliable without collapsing they well knew they 
had not brought that highway up to code maybe this will accelerate 
that program buckle said 
i880 was scheduled for improvements but the state had deferred 
the work was because officials thought the highway was structurally 
sound 
in their labs engineers tinker with theories on computers on 
how to make things strong enough to withstand jolts now they can 
correlate their computer models against what happened in heavily 
populated northern california just as they learned lessons from 
quakes in armenia mexico city and tokyo 
we cant simulate these forces in a lab the forces are so 
large buckle said we dont get very many opportunities to 
test theories or new design roles 
not all lessons are technical police and fire departments from 
new york city to phoenix ariz sent monitors to observe the 
search and rescue work at i880 where a burly dockworker was 
plucked from the crumbled concrete four days after the tuesday 
temblor 
in this business we all try to learn from each others 
disasters what were the pitfalls and what goes well said 
oakland police sgt alan whitman 
on friday five soviet engineers walked through san franciscos 
marina district an upscale neighborhood where as many as 60 
buildings crumbled or were damaged beyond repair 
the moscow experts sought to learn lessons they can use in the 
rebuilding of armenia which was rocked earlier this year by an 
earthquake of similar magnitude the death toll there was 25000 
blamed partly on shoddy construction of brick and mortar homes 
your city is much better than ours was because we had prepared 
only for a 60 richter scale earthquake said nathan kotylar 
through an interpretor both quakes registered 69 
a ninemember delegation from mexico came to learn about getting 
ready for an earthquake because that country was underprepared for 
the 1985 earthquake that ravaged mexico city 
they did not have a national system of disaster preparedness 
or a civil emergency agency said paul flores director of the 
southern california earthquake preparedness project 
he said his office had also been contacted by several states 
hoping to learn from californias experience and he expected 
delegations from japan new zealand and australia when things 
settle down 
this was a tragedy but it would be even more of a tragedy if 
we didnt learn what we could flores said 
the greatest number of earthquake sleuths concentrated on the 
epicenter on loma prieta mountain in the forest of nisene marks 
state park 10 miles from santa cruz 
two plates of earth slipped 11 miles underground with enough 
fury to move mountains flatten freeways buckle bridges crumple 
buildings and interrupt baseballs premier event the world series 
geologists and seismologists swarmed the mountain searching for 
cracks on the surface that would show where the san andreas fault 
ruptured baffled scientists have been unable to locate the main 
fissure 
we should see surface displacement of as much as 3 to 4 
feet said robert streitz a geologist with the california 
division of mines and geology 
its a jigsaw puzzle with 10000 pieces said geologist 
david schwartz 
the quake triggered 90 instruments around the area that had been 
preset to measure the speed of movement in buildings structures 
and the ground 
a comprehensive analysis of those readings will take up to a 
year although japanese experts have already asked california 
officials for them via fax machines 
experts will also focus on schools and hospitals to see how they 
survived undamaged structures will be studied for design features 
that helped them get through 
</TEXT>
