<TEXT>
maine residents face changes in the way 
they live work and play as the state phases in the nations most 
farreaching returnablecontainer law 
by next september refundable deposits will be required on every 
nondairy drink container up to a gallon in size from tiny jars 
of baby juice to liquor bottles 
all nonreturnable containers including singleserving juice 
boxes will be banned as will the plastic yokes that hold 
sixpacks together 
environmentalists are delighted with the law saying it sets a 
standard for the nation that will reduce rubbish and litter save 
energy used in producing containers and promote conservation 
basically they took a good thing and made it better pat 
franklin of the national container recycling coalition in 
washington said of maine lawmakers i really think maine will be 
leading the way on this 
others like grocer hugh holmes of farmingdale are unhappy 
holmes said his market has already run out of space for storing 
returned containers and he may have to convert an office into a 
usedcan bin 
its absolutely scary said holmes 
maines bottle law was approved by referendum in 1976 
voters resoundingly reaffirmed their support and stopped an 
industrybacked repeal campaign in 1979 
the current law similar to those in force in fewer than a dozen 
other states bans nonreturnable containers for beer and soda and 
requires consumers to pay a deposit for each can or bottle the 
deposit is refunded when the consumer turns in the container 
under legislation enacted this year that will be expanded in 
steps 
as of jan 1 anyone who brings more than 48 no deposit 
cans or bottles into the state will face fines of 20 per 
container also on that date maine joins a handful of states that 
charge deposits for liquor bottles 15 cents each 
on sept 1 all throwaway nondairy beverage containers will 
be banned 
on july 1 1991 plastic sixpack yokes which do not 
decompose readily and have been known to entangle and kill birds 
and other animals will be banned 
national soft drink association legislative analyst virginia 
mccoy said the ban is the only one of its kind in the nation 
although the legislation was the product of extended 
negotiations among diverse interests some industry officials have 
vowed to step up efforts to weaken the law before the changes take 
effect they maintain that aggressive but voluntary recycling is 
preferable 
gerber products cos rick jarman said his company will ask the 
legislature to exempt baby juice jars he warned that the added 
costs of special labeling required by the law would be passed onto 
consumers 
