<TEXT>
the master paintings and sculptures of the 
phillips collection the oldest museum of modern art in america 
are luxuriating in bright new gallery spaces after a 78 million 
expansion financed largely by a wealthy japanese businessman 
the new goh annex which opened in late september after two 
years of construction more than doubles the private museums 
exhibition to more than 30000 square feet and ushers the 
phillips into the next century with stateofthe art features 
comparable to the finest public museums 
new storage and picturehandling facilities climate control 
equipment a conservation laboratory and education classrooms made 
possible by the latest expansion the sixth since pittsburgh steel 
and banking heir duncan phillips founded the museum in 1921 in his 
redbrick mansion near dupont circle 
when phillips opened three rooms of his home as a public 
gallery his collection consisted of 237 paintings today the 
museum houses about 2500 works of art many of them acquired and 
donated by phillips and his artist wife marjorie 
the cornerstone of the museums collection is pierre auguste 
renoirs the luncheon of the boating party the impressionist 
masterpiece which phillips bought in 1923 for 125000 other 
notable holdings include el grecos the repentant peter paul 
cezannes self portrait edgar degas dancers at the bar 
and paul gauguins still life with ham 
the old masters form the backdrop for the works of modern 
artists that phillips sought to support and encourage from pierre 
bonnard to such american modernists as georgia okeeffe john marin 
and arthur dove 
the art collection grew so rapidly that it literally forced the 
phillips out of their neogeorgian mansion in 1930 and they moved 
to another home in 1960 a threestory annex with sculpture garden 
was built next door 
the new goh annex expanded the 1960 building outward and added a 
fourth floor the latest addition was named for yasuhiro goh a 
japanese art patron and pioneer of ocean transportation of liquid 
gases who donated 15 million to the phillips last year 
goh first toured the phillips during a visit to washington in 
1951 he wrote later that the museum has stayed fixed in my mind 
since that time as an expression of individual endeavor and 
initiative he said his grant was a gesture of gratitude to the 
united states where he and his three children were educated 
funds for the goh annex came mostly from individuals 
corporations and foundations the same private sources that provide 
the bulk of the museums annual 3 million operating budget the 
phillips also raised 1 million for the expansion project by 
sending 85 of its master paintings on a 1987 tour of europe and 
australia 
besides proceeds from a 3 million endowment established by 
duncan phillips before his death in 1966 the museum also receives 
an occasional federal grant from the national endowment for the 
arts to underwrite some of the four to six special exhibitions it 
mounts annually 
laughlin phillips son of the founder and former publisher of 
washingtonian magazine succeeded his father as the museums 
director 
over the years the phillips has become a beloved institution to 
a loyal and steadily growing audience of art lovers who enjoy the 
quiet unhurried ambience of the mansions stately halls as if 
they are welcome guests free to linger over a favorite painting as 
long as they wish 
by 1986 before construction began on the goh annex the number 
of annual visitors had reached 156000 
a popular phillips tradition since the 1940s has been the sunday 
afternoon series of free recitals by promising young professional 
musicians held in a long hall that was added to the mansion in 
1907 
among the musicians whose early careers included performances in 
the phillips music room were opera singer jessye norman and 
pianists emanuel ax and glenn gould 
