<TEXT>
aptos creek murmured 
softly sunday over the epicenter of northern californias deadly 
earthquake its serenity belying the ruined towns broken highways 
and bridges and shattered lives for miles around 
while crews at the collapsed nimitz freeway in oakland continued 
working amid twisted steel and crumbled concrete at a scene of 
almost unimaginable horror a few uprooted trees and minor 
landslides were the only visible signs of the quake at its 
epicenter here in the forest of nisene marks state park 
jays and squirrels chattered from the canopy of branches high 
over head a rockslide blocked the aptos creek fire road above the 
old loma prieta lumber mill 
farther up the mountain a few mossy trees had toppled across 
the trail leading to the headwaters of aptos creek tentatively 
identified by geologists as the center of the 69magnitude temblor 
for geologists the epicenter represents more symbol than 
significance said robert uhrhammer a research seismologist at the 
university of california seismographic station at berkeley 
the epicenter is just a point on the surface immediately above 
the point where the rupture first started uhrhammer said 
geologists believe that point is about 11 miles below aptos creek 
for major quakes however the point of the rupture breaks into 
a fracture many miles long that releases tremendous amounts of 
energy as geological plates slip and slide violently past each 
other 
the forest of nisene marks state park is a lush maze of ridges 
and canyons formed by the earths twists and contortions along the 
faults that run diagonally across it 
the park was created in 1963 when two brothers of a locally 
prominent farming family aided by the nature conservancy donated 
9600 acres to the state in memory of their mother nisene with 
the stipulation that it never be developed 
most of the park was clearcut in a 40year logging frenzy that 
ended in the 1920s said park ranger gerald e waggoner loggers 
cut 140 million board feet of lumber from the area 
while isolated stands of towering redwoods thousands of years 
old remain in spots the santa cruz mountains supplied much of the 
timber used to rebuild san francisco after the great quake of 1906 
at the turn of the century the loma preita mill was the largest 
in santa cruz county employing 600 workers in the summers 
waggoner said 
it was a company town he said 
the oncedenuded forest was donated to the state in 1963 and 
red alder bigleaf maples tan bark oak and secondgeneration 
redwoods are making comebacks 
this is a hidden forest here said steve shaw an aptos 
resident who paused from his jog along the fire road its not 
marked on any highways and most of us locals treat it like our own 
preserve 
other runners passing in the forest exchanged quakerelated 
pleasantries 
did your house make out ok one voice asked echoing among 
the trees 
oh we lost a chimney and a plateglass window another 
voice replied but we did pretty well 
